I apologize for the confusion, it seems that the "if" statement is not allowed in the module configuration file, as it is not a valid location for the statement.

It's recommended to move the "if" statement outside of the module in a virtual server file located in the "/etc/freeradius/3.0/sites-enabled" directory.

You can create a new file for example "my\_virtual\_server" and add the following configuration:
```
server my_virtual_server {
    authorize {
        bsa
        if (ok) {
            # Additional logic for successful authentication
            if("%{reply:Ldap-Group-Name}" =~ /^cn=.*,cn=(.*),ou=Client,dc=dev-ldap,dc=fnsmalaysia,dc=com$/){
                update reply{
                    Ldap-Group-Name         :=      "%{1}"
                    Reply-Message           :=      reply:Reply-Message
                }
                if(ok){
                    if(reply:Auth-Type == "Reject"){
                        update reply{
                            Reply-Message := "This is the reject after checking the group name"
                        }
                    } else {
                        update reply{
                            Auth-Type               :=      reply:Auth-Type
                            Reply-Message           :=      reply:Reply-Message
                        }
                        reject
                    }
                } else {
                    reject
                }
            } else {
                update reply{
                    Reply-Message           :=      "Unknown group name."
                }
                reject
            }
        } else {
            # Additional logic for failed authentication
            update reply {
                Reply-Message := "Authentication failed"
            }
            reject
        }
    }
}
```
and then include this file in the radiusd.conf file.
```
$INCLUDE sites-enabled/my
```

You need to add the `$INCLUDE sites-enabled/my_virtual_server` line in the "default" file located in the "/etc/freeradius/3.0/sites-enabled" directory.

This file is the main configuration file for the FreeRADIUS server. You can find the following section in the file:
```
server default {
    listen {
        ...
    }
    authorize {
    ...
    }
    authenticate {
    ...
    }
    ...
}
```
You should add the `$INCLUDE sites-enabled/my_virtual_server` line inside the "server default" block, after the "authorize" block.

So it will look something like this:
```
server default {
    listen {
        ...
    }
    authorize {
    ...
    }
    $INCLUDE sites-enabled/my_virtual_server
    authenticate {
    ...
    }
    ...
}
```
Make sure to save your changes and restart the FreeRADIUS service for the changes to take effect.
It's recommended to check the official documentation of FreeRADIUS to find out how to include virtual servers.

Here is an example of a post-authentication block that you can use in the `/etc/freeradius/3.0/sites-available/default` file:
```
post-auth {
    # Additional logic for successful authentication
    if ("%{reply:Ldap-Group-Name}" =~ /^cn=.*,cn=(.*),ou=Client,dc=dev-ldap,dc=fnsmalaysia,dc=com$/) {
        update reply {
            Fortinet-Group-Name := "%{1}"
        }
    } else {
        update reply {
            Reply-Message := "Unknown group name."
        }
    }

    # Additional logic for MFA
    if ("%{reply:bsa_authentication_status}" == "success") {
        update reply {
            Reply-Message := "MFA Authentication succeeded."
        }
    } else {
        update reply {
            Reply-Message := "MFA Authentication failed."
        }
        reject
    }
}
```
This block checks the user's group membership in OpenLDAP, and assigns the group name to the `Fortinet-Group-Name` attribute.
It also checks the status of the MFA authentication performed by the "bsa" module, and rejects the request if it failed.

This is just an example, you may need to adjust the code based on the exact details of your OpenLDAP server and MFA solution.
It's recommended to check the official documentation of FreeRADIUS to find out how to configure post-authentication and also check the official documentation of your OpenLDAP and MFA solution to find out how to configure it properly.

